        "name": "Alex Miller",
        "username": "alexmiller",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/alexmiller/{size}/326_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-06-04T07:44:20.764Z",
        "cooked": "<p>As rishabh found, you can raise <code>--knob_data_distribution_failure_reaction_time</code> if you\u2019re concerned about frequent storage server partitions that you\u2019d prefer to wait out.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"rishabh\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"1419\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://sea1.discourse-cdn.com/foundationdb/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/rishabh/48/540_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> rishabh:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I am not sure if its true for TLog only pod as well, whose failure will also trigger data rebalancing</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>TLogs are detected off of <code>WORKER_FAILURE_TIME</code>, which applies to mostly everything else as well.  TLog failures cause recoveries, but not data rebalancing.  (And, in 6.1, a recovery doesn\u2019t even cause data distribution to be re-initialized, as it was split off into a separate role from the master.)</p>",
